  .slide
    p.em-above: :t
      Why suppose it makes sense to ask outright which things are actions but not which things are red?
    .notes: :t
      My sense is that the action terms (‘action‘, ’agent’, ’intention’ and the rest) as used by 
      philosophers to pose a ‘fundamental question’
      are not treated as technical terms but parts of ordinary language.
      But if Clark is right about terms being used contrastively (to put it roughly),
      the question as standardly posed cannot be asked at all.
    .notes: :t
      You might think, in the case of red, that we should focus on the psychological capacity.
      The question about which things are red is trivial only because the psychological
      capacity is so shallow (mere categorization).
      But it is hard to interpret philosophers of action as doing the same,
      because psychological capacities to track agents and their actions are so
      much less well understood.

